words: I got accepted into the Jack Kent Cooke, uh, Sc, uh, Young Scholars Program,
which is a scholarship for, uh, students
going into high school that come from low income backgrounds. And that essentially provides
money that can be used for
any general increasing educational opportunity. So, for example, they will,
uh, pay for and push summer camps, um, to go and do extra stuff
during the summer between the school years. Uh, they will pay for, for me, they paid for music
lessons, they paid for computer and, uh, kinda things like that, that you wouldn't necessarily
have access to coming from a low income background that can kind of level the playing
field. So I was incredibly lucky to be able to receive
that scholarship, um, and one of the events that kind of stands out
in regards to that is the Scholars Weekend that they put on for everyone
just coming into the program, uh, when they're first beginning. Um, so
for the Young Scholars Program, that happens, uh, between eighth grade
and ninth grade, uh, so just going into high school, and you are
brought together. They held the conference in, uh, Johns Hopkins University on the east coast,
uh, the year I went. And they fly you and a parent in, and
you meet with the other fifty or so people in your cohort for the first time, and
that was a really eye opening experience because, you know, these fifty
people were drawn from fifty states across the U. S., and
hearing some of their stories and comparing them to mine was
a very sobering experience. And I realized that
there are a lot of people out there who are struggling with
financial things. There are people out there who are overcoming that, and doing
amazing things anyway, and far greater things than I thought I was doing. So,
um, yeah. There's, it was a lot to measure up to, I suppose,
but it was also just being around incredible, incredible people. Uh,
these people in my cohort, I've kept in communication with for, you know,
the past four years, and going on today, they're, you know, off still doing incredible
things. And I feel really lucky to count myself among them. And I guess
sort of the main takeaway from this Scholars Weekend was
finally feeling like I was in place
